@subheading Keyboard Events

Keyboard events have changed.  The event data related to keyboard events is no
longer stored in a structure inside @samp{iEvent}, but instead now resides
within @samp{iEvent}'s property bag.  That means the way to access the event
data has changed slightly; you now either query for the data via
@code{iEvent::Find()} to get a specific property, or you access it via the the
@samp{csKeyEventHelper} class.

Another change is that the @samp{csevKeyDown} and @samp{csevKeyUp} events have
been collapsed to a single @samp{csevKeyboard} event; the up/down information
is transported along with the event data.

The notion of @dfn{scan code} and @dfn{characters} has been replaced with
@dfn{raw} and @dfn{cooked} codes.  Basically, the raw code identifies the key
uniquely, while the cooked code is a processed version of it.  An important
aspect of this is that both the raw and cooked codes are Unicode characters.
Special keys (such as function keys) are encoded as characters from a Unicode
private use area.  Almost all event handling code should consult the raw code
because the raw code is invariant; that is, an @key{a} is an `a' even if the
@kbd{ALT} or @kbd{SHIFT} key, or both, are depressed.  This is useful for
games, for instance, which need to map keys to particular actions.  Cooked
codes are useful typically only for text input, such as within a text input
field.

You can find additional information in Crystal Space's public @sc{api}
documentation in the Event Handling and Keyboard Events sections.

To understand how to adjust your code for these changes, see the following
examples.

@example
iEvent& e = @dots{};
if (e.Type == csevKeyDown && e.Key.Code == CSKEY_ESC)
@{
@end example

@noindent
Change to:

@example
if (e.Type == csevKeyboard &&
    csKeyEventHelper::GetEventType(&e) == csKeyEventTypeDown) &&
    csKeyEventHelper::GetCookedCode(&e) == CSKEY_ESC))
@{
@end example

Another example:
@example
iEvent& e = @dots{};
switch (e.Type)
@{
  case csevKeyDown:
    Foo();
    break;
  case csevKeyUp:
    Bar();
    break;
@}
@end example

@noindent
Change to:

@example
switch (e.Type)
@{
  case csevKeyboard:
    if (csKeyEventHelper::GetEventType(&e) == csKeyEventTypeDown)
      Foo();
    else
      Bar();
    break;
@}
@end example

@subheading iGraphics2D::WriteBaseline() Deprecated

The functionality provided by @code{WriteBaseline()} is now available by 
specifying the @samp{CS_WRITE_BASELINE} flag when calling 
@code{iGraphics2D::Write()}. Hence, @code{WriteBaseline()} is superfluous and
has been deprecated.

@subheading csInitializer Changes

@code{csInitializer::RequestPlugins(csArray<csPluginRequest>)} has been added
to complement the existing @code{RequestPlugins(...)} which accepts a variable
number of arguments.  The new overload allows the list of requested plugins to
be composed at run-time, whereas the older variable-argument method required
the list be known at compile-time, which was not always convenient or possible.

@subheading Pollution Reduction

The following symbols have been renamed in order to avoid pollution of the
global namespace.

@itemize @bullet
@item
@code{STATIC_CAST()} @result{} @code{CS_STATIC_CAST()}
@item
@code{DYNAMIC_CAST()} @result{} @code{CS_DYNAMIC_CAST()}
@item
@code{REINTERPRET_CAST()} @result{} @code{CS_REINTERPRET_CAST()}
@item
@code{CONST_CAST()} @result{} @code{CS_CONST_CAST()}
@end itemize

@subheading Texture manager change
@cindex @code{iTextureManager}
@cindex @code{SetVerbose}

The @code{iTextureManager::SetVerbose()} function has been removed. It
was not useful.

@subheading Font changes
@cindex @code{iFontServer}
@cindex @code{LoadFont}
@cindex @code{iFont}
@cindex @code{SetSize}

@code{iFont::SetSize()} has been removed. Instead, the font size is 
supplied when the font is created with @code{iFontServer::LoadFont()}.
This change has been made to fix the problem that multiple LoadFont()
calls were returning the same instance of a font, and thus subsequent calls 
of @code{SetSize()} affected a font globally (e.g. all Arial fonts would
be the same size). The new behaviour is to return only an existing
instance of a font when both the font name and font size match.  If there is
no existing instance with the requested name and size, then a new instance
is created and returned.

Font-related client code, such as the following:

@example
csRef<iFont> font = fontserver->LoadFont ("myfont.ttf");
font->SetSize (23);
g2d->Write (font, @dots{});
@end example

@noindent
Should be changed to:

@example
csRef<iFont> font = fontserver->LoadFont ("myfont.ttf", 23);
g2d->Write (font, @dots{});
@end example

@subheading Mesh flag change
@cindex @code{CS_ENTITY_INVISIBLE}
@cindex @code{CS_ENTITY_INVISIBLEMESH}
@cindex @code{CS_ENTITY_NOHITBEAM}

There is a new flag @code{CS_ENTITY_INVISIBLEMESH} which controls visibility
(and ONLY visibility) of a mesh. There is also a new flag
@code{CS_ENTITY_NOHITBEAM} which controls if calling @code{HitBeam()} will
ever return that mesh. The old @code{CS_ENTITY_INVISIBLE} has been changed
so that it is now a combination of both flags.

An important change is that setting the @code{CS_ENTITY_INVISIBLEMESH} flag
on a parent in a hierarchy will no longer make the children invisible. You
now have to set the invisible flag manually on all children in the hierarchy.

@subheading Skeletal Sprites
@cindex @code{iSkeletonState}
@cindex @code{iSkeletonState}
@cindex @code{iSkeletonLimbState}
@cindex @code{iSkeletonConnection}
@cindex @code{iSkeletonConnectionState}
@cindex @code{iMotionTemplate}
@cindex @code{iMotionManager}
@cindex @code{iSkeletonBone}

Support for skeletal sprites has been removed, along with the following related
interfaces.  Use the @samp{sprcal3d} mesh object instead.  It is more flexible
and works correctly.  These interfaces have been retired:

